<DocsLayout title="What is a Zero-Day?">

<h1>What is a Zero-Day?</h1>

<p class="lead">
A <strong>zero-day vulnerability</strong> is a software security flaw that is
unknown to the software vendor or has no patch available. Since developers have
had <strong>zero days</strong> to fix it, attackers may exploit it before users
can protect themselves.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>How Does a Zero-Day Happen?</h2>

<ol>
  <li>A hidden bug exists in software.</li>
  <li>A security researcher or attacker discovers it.</li>
  <li>If attackers find it first, they can build an exploit.</li>
  <li>The vendor develops and releases a security patch.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Why Are Zero-Day Vulnerabilities Dangerous?</h2>

<ul>
  <li>They can be exploited before a patch exists.</li>
  <li>Traditional antivirus software may not detect new exploits.</li>
  <li>They often target governments, businesses, and critical infrastructure.</li>
  <li>Successful attacks can lead to data theft, ransomware, or system compromise.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Real-World Example</h2>

<div class="example">
  <h3>Stuxnet (2010)</h3>

  <p>
    Stuxnet was one of the most sophisticated cyber weapons ever discovered.
    It used multiple Windows zero-day vulnerabilities to target industrial
    control systems and demonstrated how powerful zero-day exploits can be.
  </p>
</div>

<h2>Key Takeaways</h2>

<div class="tips">

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>🔍 Unknown</strong>
    <p>The vulnerability is not yet publicly known or patched.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>⚠️ High Risk</strong>
    <p>Attackers can exploit systems before defenders have a fix.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>🛡️ Protection</strong>
    <p>Regular updates, monitoring, and responsible disclosure reduce risk.</p>
  </div>

</div>

